00:31:31.250 --> 00:31:33.250
are performing in the classroom

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:35.453
and what really excited me about listening

00:31:35.453 --> 00:31:40.566
to your program and the Khan Academy

00:31:40.566 --> 00:31:43.285
is how it touches so
many different elements

00:31:43.285 --> 00:31:45.550
that are frustrating to the
teachers in the classroom

00:31:45.550 --> 00:31:48.788
where they're getting more paperwork

00:31:48.788 --> 00:31:51.759
of tracking kids rather than teaching kids

00:31:51.759 --> 00:31:54.613
which takes our time away from teaching

00:31:54.613 --> 00:31:57.551
and knowing what our
students are really doing

00:31:57.551 --> 00:32:01.110
and so this provides documenting
of what they are doing.

00:32:01.110 --> 00:32:03.651
It also, really addresses the fact that

00:32:03.651 --> 00:32:05.952
every child is an individual learner

00:32:05.952 --> 00:32:08.278
and they really need to
learn at their own pace,

00:32:08.278 --> 00:32:09.865
their own maturity level

00:32:09.865 --> 00:32:13.451
and how income in coming
in, so in tutoring

00:32:13.451 --> 00:32:16.062
I have a picture up of when I'm talking

00:32:16.062 --> 00:32:17.392
to the kids and their parents and helping

00:32:17.392 --> 00:32:19.178
them understand how important it is in

00:32:19.178 --> 00:32:22.350
the elementary level that
if they're sick one day

00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:26.042
and they miss that learning
lesson in math that day,

00:32:26.042 --> 00:32:28.383
how much it affects the whole foundation

00:32:28.383 --> 00:32:30.151
of building a house on math.

00:32:30.151 --> 00:32:33.164
Tom: Yeah. Miss one piece
and you're in trouble.

00:32:33.164 --> 00:32:34.652
Here you can go back and get it.

00:32:34.652 --> 00:32:36.154
Do you think this will
put you out of business

00:32:36.154 --> 00:32:37.960
with your tutoring service, Maxine?

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:40.851
Maxine: No. I would totally use it and

00:32:40.851 --> 00:32:42.480
this reason I don't think we're going

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:44.832
to lose our teachers
because we still need,

00:32:44.832 --> 00:32:50.952
in our humanity, is that real person there

00:32:50.952 --> 00:32:54.038
to help the student say, "Yes."

00:32:54.038 --> 00:32:57.293
It's wonderful and I have
not looked at your program

00:32:57.293 --> 00:33:02.150
but I know that just to have the awards

00:33:02.150 --> 00:33:04.682
and I love it! That it's not that you got

00:33:04.682 --> 00:33:06.766
the correct answer, it's the fact that you

00:33:06.766 --> 00:33:08.680
keep on persevering.

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:11.320
When I was in college
I had a science class.

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:13.290
It was on ecology and it
was one of the questions

00:33:13.290 --> 00:33:15.711
and we were on the
computer and the first time

00:33:15.711 --> 00:33:17.513
I did it I got the
answer wrong and it says,

00:33:17.513 --> 00:33:20.461
"Try again. Try again." The computer did

00:33:20.461 --> 00:33:22.920
because the teacher had
programmed that into it

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:25.794
because it was like real daunting to me

00:33:25.794 --> 00:33:27.539
because I'm not a science person.

00:33:27.539 --> 00:33:28.215
Tom: Yep.

00:33:28.215 --> 00:33:30.407
Maxine: But then the next time, you know,

00:33:30.407 --> 00:33:31.998
I did it again and I got
it wrong and he says,

00:33:31.998 --> 00:33:34.551
"Try one more time for dear old mom."

00:33:34.551 --> 00:33:35.458
(laughing)

00:33:35.458 --> 00:33:37.741
And it had just stuck with
me my whole life going,

00:33:37.741 --> 00:33:40.543
"Yeah, you just keep
working at something."

00:33:40.543 --> 00:33:42.129
Tom: That little bit to
get you over the hump.

00:33:42.129 --> 00:33:45.298
Maxine, I appreciate
your call very much dear.

00:33:45.298 --> 00:33:46.351
Khan: I think we might incorporate

00:33:46.351 --> 00:33:47.751
the dear old mom idea.

00:33:47.751 --> 00:33:48.420
(laughing)

00:33:48.420 --> 00:33:50.545
Tom: One more time for dear old mom.

00:33:50.545 --> 00:33:52.251
You know, there have been so many people

00:33:52.251 --> 00:33:55.802
working on this digital
future for education, Salman.

00:33:55.802 --> 00:33:57.451
You know that. My friend, Art Bardage,

00:33:57.451 --> 00:33:59.392
with the Naval Learning at
Cambridge, Massachusetts

00:33:59.392 --> 00:34:00.552
doing great work on this.

00:34:00.552 --> 00:34:01.987
A big admirer of what you're doing.

00:34:01.987 --> 00:34:03.559
He says, "Your format
is perfect. Your timing

00:34:03.559 --> 00:34:06.542
is perfect." But his question to you and

00:34:06.542 --> 00:34:08.604
it's kind of implicit,
you get a call there

00:34:08.604 --> 00:34:12.968
from Kentucky or, you
know, not all schools

00:34:12.968 --> 00:34:14.939
have all this technology in them.

00:34:14.939 --> 00:34:19.115
In big urban areas, in
rural areas, not everybody

00:34:19.115 --> 00:34:20.799
has figured out how to use technology

00:34:20.799 --> 00:34:21.890
in the classroom yet.

00:34:21.890 --> 00:34:23.751
I mean, how do you envision the future

00:34:23.751 --> 00:34:27.440
of technology in the classroom.
What does it look like?

00:34:27.440 --> 00:34:28.468
What's your vision?

00:34:28.468 --> 00:34:31.974
Khan: Yeah, no. It's a
very legitimate point.

00:34:31.974 --> 00:34:33.842
I think what's happened and this is

00:34:33.842 --> 00:34:36.279
since I was a kid in the 80's, you know,

00:34:36.279 --> 00:34:38.973
we had computer labs then and even then

00:34:38.973 --> 00:34:40.477
they were completely
un-utilized because no one

00:34:40.477 --> 00:34:41.377
really knew what to do with them.

00:34:41.377 --> 00:34:42.855
We'd go in for like 20
minutes and they'd say,

00:34:42.855 --> 00:34:44.903
"Hey, put a diskette in
it. Okay, you've booted it,

00:34:44.903 --> 00:34:46.381
now go back to math class."
Or something like that.

00:34:46.381 --> 00:34:47.053
Tom: Right.

00:34:47.053 --> 00:34:49.210
Khan: And so, what we think is now

00:34:49.210 --> 00:34:52.144
we are getting a very tangible thing to do

00:34:52.144 --> 00:34:54.088
with the technology
and it's not technology

00:34:54.088 --> 00:34:55.669
for technology's sake.
It's about technology

00:34:55.669 --> 00:34:57.922
to enable humanity and
the rest of the curriculum

00:34:57.922 --> 00:35:01.415
and so, what we think is,
is that now this exists

00:35:01.415 --> 00:35:03.256
there's actually now a reason to do it

00:35:03.256 --> 00:35:06.184
and it's actually not
expensive when you compare it

00:35:06.184 --> 00:35:06.918
with other things.

00:35:06.918 --> 00:35:10.758
Right now you can get
a kind of a handheld PC

00:35:10.758 --> 00:35:13.163
for $200 that can last 4 years.

00:35:13.163 --> 00:35:17.122
That's $50 a year and it can be shared

00:35:17.122 --> 00:35:19.373
by multiple students, so
it actually goes down to

00:35:19.373 --> 00:35:22.472
only $10 or $20 per student per year,

00:35:22.472 --> 00:35:25.168
which is super cost
effective even compared

00:35:25.168 --> 00:35:28.663
to textbooks or, and
especially the $8000-$10,000

00:35:28.663 --> 00:35:30.372
a year that a lot of public school systems

00:35:30.372 --> 00:35:32.351
might spend on, per pupil.

00:35:32.351 --> 00:35:33.804
Tom: Well, take it from there though.

00:35:33.804 --> 00:35:35.652
Let's say, I don't know,
Bill Gates gives you

00:35:35.652 --> 00:35:38.351
$50 or $100 billion, you got all the money

00:35:38.351 --> 00:35:39.869
in the world to work on this and here's

00:35:39.869 --> 00:35:41.264
the American education system.

00:35:41.264 --> 00:35:43.514
Let's say you can get your
technology in everywhere.

00:35:43.514 --> 00:35:45.945
What is the actually education look like

00:35:45.945 --> 00:35:49.451
in a fully technology empowered American

00:35:49.451 --> 00:35:51.087
education system? What's it look like?

00:35:51.625 --> 00:35:53.403
Khan: I think what
you'll see and, you know,

00:35:53.403 --> 00:35:55.750
we want to see more and
more of this, is the school

00:35:55.750 --> 00:35:57.753
of the future is going to be, it's kind of

00:35:57.753 --> 00:36:00.257
going to revert back to
the one room school house

00:36:00.257 --> 00:36:01.904
where you have kids of all ages at all

00:36:01.904 --> 00:36:04.051
different skill levels.
They might not even be kids.

00:36:04.481 --> 00:36:06.500
Even college students,
they're all in that one room

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:08.727
and they're all learning
at their own pace.

00:36:09.527 --> 00:36:11.843
It frees up time for them to do things

00:36:11.843 --> 00:36:14.020
that are actual expressions
of their creativity,

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:16.713
so actually writing computer programs,

00:36:16.713 --> 00:36:19.339
building robots, composing
music, whatever it is.

00:36:19.985 --> 00:36:22.291
There's time freed up
to do that and they have

00:36:22.291 --> 00:36:24.950
mentors and teachers that
are constantly walking around

00:36:24.950 --> 00:36:27.643
and mentoring them in these projects

00:36:27.643 --> 00:36:29.601
and getting them past the hurdles the way

00:36:29.601 --> 00:36:31.223
that Courtney is doing in her class

00:36:31.223 --> 00:36:32.403
and I want to point on,
this is the interesting

00:36:32.403 --> 00:36:34.654
thing, there's no reason
why it's just the US.

00:36:34.654 --> 00:36:37.336
It's really a world wide phenomenon here.

00:36:37.336 --> 00:36:39.251
We're actually right now
translating the content

00:36:39.251 --> 00:36:42.409
into 10 languages and the idea is that

00:36:42.409 --> 00:36:44.492
we also want to eventually
localize the software

00:36:44.492 --> 00:36:46.758
so that a student anywhere can start to

00:36:46.758 --> 00:36:48.145
get a pretty good scaffold.

00:36:48.145 --> 00:36:49.855
And as important as a
self-paced learning is

00:36:49.855 --> 00:36:52.243
in the US and it's super important here,

00:36:52.243 --> 00:36:54.861
it's even more important
for a kid in India

00:36:54.861 --> 00:36:58.767
who has to work half the day or who has

00:36:58.767 --> 00:37:00.659
never learned to read or
has been out of school

00:37:00.659 --> 00:37:01.995
for 5 or 6 years.

00:37:01.995 --> 00:37:05.753
Tom: So tech powered, self-paced? Is that

00:37:05.753 --> 00:37:09.157
a systemic change that
can fix our problems?

00:37:09.157 --> 00:37:10.913
You've heard the news out today, you know,

00:37:10.913 --> 00:37:13.114
the new ACT scores for college admissions

00:37:13.114 --> 00:37:16.355
showing that just one
in 4 American graduates

00:37:16.355 --> 00:37:18.664
in the class of 2011 who
took the exam, met their

00:37:18.664 --> 00:37:22.327
4 key benchmarks. Can you put self-pacing

00:37:22.327 --> 00:37:25.894
and this kind of, you know,
series of tech lectures,

00:37:25.894 --> 00:37:27.651
technology in the classroom and fix that

00:37:27.651 --> 00:37:29.117
or does it take something else?

00:37:29.117 --> 00:37:30.024
Something more?

00:37:31.009 --> 00:37:33.114
Khan: It's an open
question. We'll find out.

00:37:33.114 --> 00:37:35.027
The unfortunate thing is
right now based on things

00:37:35.027 --> 00:37:37.914
like ACT scores or some
of these state exams

00:37:37.914 --> 00:37:40.552
to graduate, a lot of students,
I mean, if you just look

00:37:40.552 --> 00:37:42.085
at the stats of how many
students have to take

00:37:42.085 --> 00:37:44.754
remedial math or college algebra when

00:37:44.754 --> 00:37:47.246
they get to college,
if they even get there,

00:37:47.246 --> 00:37:51.250
it's a huge number. I
mean, it's a majority

00:37:51.250 --> 00:37:55.958
and it makes you think, well
what has happened to them

00:37:55.958 --> 00:37:57.366
over the course of their last 7, 8 years

00:37:57.366 --> 00:37:59.162
in high school and in
middle school and the

00:37:59.162 --> 00:38:01.742
answer isn't, it's actually not
a problem with the teachers,

00:38:01.742 --> 00:38:02.353
it's not a problem with the students.

00:38:02.353 --> 00:38:03.828
It's exactly what the
teacher from Kentucky

00:38:03.828 --> 00:38:06.257
was pointing out is
that, if you miss one day

00:38:06.257 --> 00:38:08.351
of school in third
grade or you don't learn

00:38:08.351 --> 00:38:10.826
your multiplication tables
properly or you don't

00:38:10.826 --> 00:38:13.498
100% master negative numbers, that's going

00:38:13.498 --> 00:38:15.012
to be a gap in your
foundation that's going

00:38:15.012 --> 00:38:16.902
to last with you your
lifetime and at some point

00:38:16.902 --> 00:38:19.351
that gap is going to
allow something to crumble

00:38:19.351 --> 00:38:20.947
when you get to algebra or calculus.

00:38:20.947 --> 00:38:23.075
And we're seeing that across the board.

00:38:23.075 --> 00:38:25.349
So, we hope that what we're doing here

00:38:25.349 --> 00:38:27.606
can really address that
and really allow people

00:38:27.606 --> 00:38:30.889
to go back and make sure
they have 100% foundation

00:38:30.889 --> 00:38:32.949
so that they can stay on a track.

00:38:33.518 --> 00:38:35.357
Tom: Wired Magazine
says you never intended

00:38:35.357 --> 00:38:37.989
to become an education revolutionary.

00:38:37.989 --> 00:38:40.396
Are you an education
revolutionary, Salman Khan?

00:38:40.612 --> 00:38:42.358
Khan: You know, we don't want to-

00:38:42.358 --> 00:38:44.361
The one thing that we shy away from

00:38:44.361 --> 00:38:47.251
is trying to make more
of it than what it is.

00:38:47.251 --> 00:38:49.549
We hope it can be as much as possible, but

00:38:49.549 --> 00:38:52.455
our focus on our team,
we generally just want

00:38:52.455 --> 00:38:54.967
to keep building stuff,
seeing how it works,

00:38:54.967 --> 00:38:57.695
looking at the data,
getting feedback from users

00:38:57.695 --> 00:38:59.335
and making it better and
better, and exploring

00:38:59.335 --> 00:39:02.131
where it can be used and really avoid

00:39:02.131 --> 00:39:04.445
getting into, kind of, the more
political debates about it.

00:39:04.445 --> 00:39:05.627
Tom: Well, I don't know if you're going to

00:39:05.627 --> 00:39:07.632
be able to avoid that in
the world of education.

00:39:07.632 --> 00:39:08.863
Khan: (laughing) That's what I'm thinking.

