Peter: Hi, Tom. Great to be here.

00:40:45.820 --> 00:40:49.059
Tom: So, what exactly is
the course going to cover?

00:40:49.059 --> 00:40:52.487
What's the range here? Is it
an introductory course in AI?

00:40:52.487 --> 00:40:54.858
Peter: It's the introductory course

00:40:54.858 --> 00:40:56.137
in Artificial Intelligence.

00:40:56.137 --> 00:40:59.076
The standard course is taught at Stanford

00:40:59.076 --> 00:41:02.910
and it does require
prerequisites in mathematics

00:41:02.910 --> 00:41:05.754
and programming, so
it's not an introductory

00:41:05.754 --> 00:41:08.738
course for anyone, but
for somebody who has

00:41:08.738 --> 00:41:10.071
that kind of background.

00:41:10.071 --> 00:41:11.651
Tom: So, how do you determine who has

00:41:11.651 --> 00:41:15.074
the prerequisite background to show up

00:41:15.074 --> 00:41:18.352
and take, very remotely,
your free online course.

00:41:18.352 --> 00:41:20.991
Peter: Well, we've offered it for anybody

00:41:20.991 --> 00:41:23.215
to sign up and we've made clear of what

00:41:23.215 --> 00:41:24.984
the syllabus is, what we're going to cover

00:41:24.984 --> 00:41:28.255
and tried to describe what's required,

00:41:28.255 --> 00:41:32.045
what background is required and then it's

00:41:32.045 --> 00:41:34.076
up to the students to do their work.

00:41:34.076 --> 00:41:36.951
We wanted to make the course, such that,

00:41:36.951 --> 00:41:41.827
it's as similar as we can
make it to a live course

00:41:41.827 --> 00:41:46.727
taught on campus. There's
lots of materials online.

00:41:46.727 --> 00:41:49.152
You know, I've heard
about Sal. I've talked

00:41:49.152 --> 00:41:52.651
with Sal before and he's
one of the inspirations

00:41:52.651 --> 00:41:53.751
for what we've done.

