00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:53.851
we'll definitely get a couple thousand.

00:42:53.851 --> 00:42:55.851
We had no idea that we were
going to get this many.

00:42:55.851 --> 00:42:59.810
Now, so far we only have
their email addresses,

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:02.153
so that's not a work to ask out of them.

00:43:02.153 --> 00:43:02.816
Tom: Right.

00:43:02.816 --> 00:43:04.460
Peter: So, when they start having to do

00:43:04.460 --> 00:43:07.252
the actual homework, we
expect some of them will drop.

00:43:07.252 --> 00:43:09.931
Tom: Interest from 175
countries around the world,

00:43:09.931 --> 00:43:12.351
85,000 now signed up.
What do you make of that?

00:43:12.351 --> 00:43:15.949
How do you interpret that,
what seems like enormous

00:43:15.949 --> 00:43:18.213
amount of interest and people, as you say,

00:43:18.213 --> 00:43:19.619
you'll see what happens, but so far,

00:43:19.619 --> 00:43:21.020
willing to put their hand up and say,

00:43:21.020 --> 00:43:23.344
"I want to study artificial
intelligence with

00:43:23.344 --> 00:43:25.042
you guys maybe thousands of miles away

00:43:25.042 --> 00:43:26.454
at Stanford University."

00:43:27.054 --> 00:43:28.841
Peter: Yeah, it's a tremendous response.

00:43:30.348 --> 00:43:32.267
I think it just shows that
there's lot of interest

00:43:32.267 --> 00:43:35.445
out there that people want to have access

00:43:35.445 --> 00:43:37.751
to this type of material.
They want to learn.

00:43:37.751 --> 00:43:41.008
They think this is an interesting topic,

00:43:41.008 --> 00:43:42.986
interesting set of teachers, maybe?

00:43:44.402 --> 00:43:46.338
And Stanford is a well-known university

00:43:46.338 --> 00:43:49.850
and bringing all those
things together and making

00:43:49.850 --> 00:43:53.852
them available for free in a real course

00:43:53.852 --> 00:43:57.150
where you can be evaluated,
it's just something

00:43:57.150 --> 00:43:58.489
that's a little bit novel.

00:43:58.827 --> 00:44:01.252
Lot's of people have done similar types

00:44:01.252 --> 00:44:03.568
of approaches before, but
we've put all the pieces

00:44:03.568 --> 00:44:05.346
together in just a slightly different way.

00:44:05.346 --> 00:44:07.252
Tom: And you talk about a small world.

00:44:07.252 --> 00:44:09.566
Here, you're out, presumably as director

00:44:09.566 --> 00:44:11.436
of research at Google,
former NASA scientist.

00:44:11.436 --> 00:44:12.958
You're out on the cutting edge of AI.

00:44:12.958 --> 00:44:15.169
You're going to be
instructing people literally

00:44:15.169 --> 00:44:17.197
from around the world.

00:44:17.197 --> 00:44:20.248
I'm trying to take on
board what this trend

00:44:20.248 --> 00:44:23.527
that you're part of, means
about global understanding

00:44:23.527 --> 00:44:27.136
at the cutting edge of high science?

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:31.170
Does this speed the
creation of a real, sort of,

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:34.189
homogeneous global community
of scientific insight.

00:44:34.189 --> 00:44:36.257
Peter: I hope so. That's
what we're trying to do.

00:44:36.257 --> 00:44:38.152
You know, we're trying to make it easier

00:44:38.152 --> 00:44:41.445
for more people to get access to this type

00:44:41.445 --> 00:44:44.545
of information, so you
don't have to get a PhD

00:44:44.545 --> 00:44:47.751
to study AI, you can
try it out in a format

00:44:47.751 --> 00:44:51.727
that's easier and see if
it makes sense for you.

00:44:51.727 --> 00:44:54.539
Tom: Who is AI useful too?

00:44:54.539 --> 00:44:56.111
Do you have to be an
engineer in a high tech

00:44:56.111 --> 00:44:58.243
company for this to be useful?

00:44:58.243 --> 00:45:00.655
What's the range of profiles of people

00:45:00.655 --> 00:45:03.150
for whom you think this might be valuable?

00:45:05.409 --> 00:45:08.831
Peter: I guess, to
apply all the techniques

00:45:08.831 --> 00:45:11.150
to make more sense to be in some type

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.471
of a company. I think that it's broader

00:45:14.471 --> 00:45:17.040
than just the computer
industry so you're seeing

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:22.058
applications in biology,
in finance, sort of

00:45:22.058 --> 00:45:25.958
across the board in any type of profession

00:45:25.958 --> 00:45:29.050
that's dealing with interpreting data,

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:32.843
interpreting uncertainty,
these techniques are useful.

00:45:32.843 --> 00:45:36.100
Tom: And does Google, you're
a director of research

00:45:36.100 --> 00:45:37.659
there, do they have
any concern that you're

00:45:37.659 --> 00:45:39.455
giving away the store to the world?

00:45:40.055 --> 00:45:42.845
Peter: No, Google's been
extremely supportive.

00:45:42.845 --> 00:45:45.385
It's always been our mission to provide

00:45:45.385 --> 00:45:48.544
accessed information and
this is just one more

00:45:48.544 --> 00:45:51.551
way to do it and they're behind it 100%.

00:45:51.551 --> 00:45:54.052
Tom: Okay, we've got a lot
of listeners right now.

00:45:54.052 --> 00:45:56.350
What's a, or the, key
insight that you hope

00:45:56.350 --> 00:46:00.165
people come away from
a semester of AI with?

00:46:00.165 --> 00:46:02.279
A, sort of, is there some
fundamental orientation

00:46:02.279 --> 00:46:04.471
toward artificial
intelligence or fundamental

00:46:04.471 --> 00:46:06.267
piece of understanding
you hope people get?

00:46:07.128 --> 00:46:10.700
Peter: I guess, to try to demystify it,

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:14.496
so people have visions of robots

00:46:14.496 --> 00:46:17.780
from science fiction stories without quite

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:20.647
understanding how they
got there, so we want

00:46:20.647 --> 00:46:26.082
to show that by analyzing,
using mathematical

00:46:26.082 --> 00:46:27.951
techniques, using programming techniques

00:46:27.951 --> 00:46:30.146
that you could understand what it is that

00:46:30.146 --> 00:46:33.166
a robot could do or not do, understand

00:46:33.166 --> 00:46:36.851
how to interpret data in the
world and make sense of it.

00:46:36.851 --> 00:46:40.466
Tom: And will computer's
intelligence outpace

00:46:40.466 --> 00:46:42.751
our own? Has it already
when you add it all up?

00:46:43.489 --> 00:46:46.251
Peter: I don't really think
about it as outpacing.

00:46:46.251 --> 00:46:48.636
I think of it as augmenting.

00:46:49.328 --> 00:46:53.048
So, there's already
places where a computer

00:46:53.048 --> 00:46:55.352
outpaces us. My computer is much better

00:46:55.352 --> 00:46:58.748
at multiplying 10 digit numbers than I am

00:46:58.748 --> 00:47:01.751
and there's places where people are better

00:47:01.751 --> 00:47:03.978
than computers, so I think
how can we work together?

00:47:04.163 --> 00:47:06.498
Tom: Peter Norvig, director
of research at Google,

00:47:06.498 --> 00:47:08.533
guest lecturer at Stanford University.

00:47:08.533 --> 00:47:10.351
He'll be teaching with Sebastian Thrun,

00:47:10.351 --> 00:47:13.158
a free online course in
artificial intelligence

00:47:13.158 --> 00:47:17.250
this fall 85,000 people
already signed up for that

00:47:17.250 --> 00:47:19.200
from right around the world.

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:21.035
Peter Norvig in Mountain View, California.

00:47:21.035 --> 00:47:22.708
Thank you very much for
being with us today.

00:47:22.708 --> 00:47:23.592
Peter: Thanks, Tom.

00:47:23.592 --> 00:47:24.804
Tom: Listeners, thanks for joining us.

00:47:24.804 --> 00:47:27.320
I'm Tom Ashbrook. This is On Point.

